posts.subject: Texture Mapping and COVID-19
posts.body:
I began this work few months ago with the idea to work with standard DICOM files, but i cannot do this for various reasons, and because of this i decided to publish this data on the web. Finally GalactiChan is working and because of this i can post all elaborated data also here! (you can find all data in the alleged zip file)

link to my blog: https://antonellogalati.com/2020/12/25/texture-mapping-e-covid-19/

My objective was try to identify what parameters AI are using to diagnose COVID-19 pneumonia by evaluating Computed Tomografy images (this method, called radiomics, is an emerging field in radiology. The last study that i've found about radiomics and COVID-19 was written by Jin et al. in 2020 in China by using a very large dataset.

To reach my objective i recovered some JPEG photos of CT images from public databases (Radiopaedia and the Italian SIRM database) and created the maps of GLCM texture indicators by using LifeX software; after that i visually evaluated them. I cannot use DICOM files because i don't have a contact with a radiology department, anyway i hope that these data can be useful to anyone to write a study by using DICOM files (i noted also that some AI softwares use JPG file format).

Links:

LifeX software: https://lifexsoft.org/

Radiopaedia: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/covid-19-4

SIRM database: https://www.sirm.org/category/senza-categoria/covid-19/

posts.subject: Introduction and limits
posts.body:
THe JPG file format is very different from DICOM format because of some reasons:

-CT DICOM are 3D files, pics are 2D files (single slices)
-CT DICOM use Hounsfield Units (2000 gray levels), JPG are limited to 256 gray levels (linearly rescaled by using a gray colorscale and the lung window).

Anyway to calculate the GLCM matrix HU scale is rescaled to few gray levels and because of this the results of this study schould not show too many differences from a DICOM study rescaled with the same window limits. The similarity of the data obtained by two different photos datasets (SIRM and Radiopaedia) point also tho this consideration.

posts.subject: Material and methods
posts.body: I extracted the lung parenchyma by using hand-drawn ROIs (Region of Interest) to reduce the CPU power necessary for calculations. All images was rescaled to 64 gray levels (size of bin to 4) before calculating pixel-based GLCM matrices and regional indicators values by using a kernel with a diameter of 7 pixels.

posts.subject: COVID-19 pneumonia
posts.body:
The typical lesions of this disease show high values of GLCM disorder indicators like dissimilary, entropy and contrast (in al pics the color scale increases values from blue to red). Order indicators like energy and homogeneity show no differences from the background. Very dense structures like blood vessels (filled with contrast agent) and the thorax wall show very high levels of energy and homogeneity due to an artifact caused by image rescaling (very high values are cut and because of this higher values are identical)

example shown in this post: https://radiopaedia.org/cases/covid-19-pneumonia-7

posts.subject: follow up
posts.body: From the SIRM database i recovered 2 image sets obtained from the same patients after healing (case 34) and with different lesions that progress differently (case 33). I observed that lesions that go to heal become more dense and show reduced values of disorder indicators (dissimilarity, entropy and contrast), at the contrary a worse prognosis seems to be associated with an increase of these indicator values. These data needs to be verifies with a larger sample.

posts.subject: normal lung (healthy control)
posts.body:
Normal lung parechyma appears homogeneous to all indicators, iso-hypointense with dissimilarity, entropy and contrast; isointense with energy and homogeneity. Artifacts can be seen within blood vessels and thorax wall (as described above) and near little blood vessels that can show false increased values of disorders indicators because of local inhomogeneity caused by puntiform accumulation of contrast media near very hypodense lung parenchyma

https://radiopaedia.org/cases/normal-chest-ct-lung-window-1?lang=us

posts.subject: Differential diagnosis
posts.body: all cases of other diseases taken from Radiopaedia seems to show different patterns of distributions of the indicators in diferent diseases. This maybe could be used in differential diagnosis. Larger samples are needed

posts.subject: H1N1 influenza
posts.body:
This case show increased levels of dissimilarity entropy and contrast with higher background ratio compared to COVID pneumonia and "molded appearance". Slighty reduced levels of energy and homogeneity are observed in H1N1 influenza but not in COVID-19 pneumonia

https://radiopaedia.org/cases/influenza-a-h1n1-pneumonia?lang=us

posts.subject: pulmonary haemorrhage
posts.body:
pulmonary haemorrhage can be seen as an area with very high energy and homogeneity values. (this example is located at the left lung base)


https://radiopaedia.org/cases/pulmonary-haemorrhage-3

posts.subject: Cryptogenic organising pneumonia - case 1
posts.body:
Can show very different patterns. 

Case 1: leasions appear to have slight increased energy and homogeneity values and reduced values of entropy, dissimilarity and contrast)


https://radiopaedia.org/cases/cryptogenic-organising-pneumonia

posts.subject: Cryptogenic organising pneumonia - case 2
posts.body:
Increased values of entropy, dissimilarity and contrast

https://radiopaedia.org/cases/cryptogenic-organising-pneumonia-2

posts.subject: Citomegalovirus pneumonia
posts.body:
Lesions appears hyperintense at GLCM entropy, contrast and dissimilarity showing poorly defined margins, while GLCM energy and homogeneity show low values with molded appearance

https://radiopaedia.org/cases/cytomegalovirus-pneumonia-in-a-renal-transplant-patient

posts.subject: chronic eosinophilic pneumonia
posts.body:
Lesions are very inhomogeneous to all indicators. Areas with very high leves of energy and homogeneity can be observed in the context of a global increase of entropy, dissimilarity and contrast

https://radiopaedia.org/cases/chronic-eosinophilic-pneumonia

posts.subject: Cardiogenic pulmonary oedema
posts.body:
Cannot be discerned from the background by using any indicator. Only the border of the pleural effusion is visible


https://radiopaedia.org/cases/cardiogenic-pulmonary-oedema

posts.subject: Rheumathoid artritis
posts.body: Blood vessels shown very high values of GLCM entropy, dissimilarity and contrast with "molded" appearance. the parechyma appear hypointense at GLCM homogeneity

posts.subject: non-specific interstitial pneumonitis
posts.body:
Similar to Rheumathoid Artritis, but entropy, dissimilarity and contrast show a lower background ratio compared to AR

https://radiopaedia.org/cases/non-specific-interstitial-pneumonitis-secondary-to-connective-tissue-disease-1?lang=us

posts.subject: Pneumocystis Carinii Pneumonia
posts.body: Lesions appear inhomogeneous: globally isointense to all indicators with some areas with higher entropy, dissimilarity and contrast values

posts.subject: Acute Eosinophilic Pneumonia
posts.body: Lesions show very high values of entropy, dissimilarity and contrast while the normal parechyma appears wih very high levels of energy and homogeneity. Both lesions and parenchyma show "molded" appearance with well defined margins

posts.subject: Sarcoidosis
posts.body: Lung lesions show increased values of entropy, dissimilarity and contrast with molded appearance near mediastinum and poorly defined margins near thorax wall.
